import yahoo_fin.stock_info as si
import pandas as pd

DATA COLLECTION

We will be using a list of S&P 500 companies that have already been labeled in terms of sector with the full company name as well as a third party web scraping API to search said companies on Yahoo Finance. The reason we are using the S&P 500 companies is because they are float-adjusting, meaning they only count the shares available to the public. This means that they are publicly traded and the information released to the public will directly influence the stock prices.

The Yahoo_fin API can also provide types of reports for stocks such as calls, puts, and real-time information if you want to create a responsive application. For now, however, we will only focus on valuations which expect a company to increase in value as time goes on.

Resources can be found here:

S&P 500 Companies: https://github.com/datasets/s-and-p-500-companies/blob/master/data/constituents.csv

Yahoo_fin: http://theautomatic.net/yahoo_fin-documentation/

We are now able to scrape them based on "Tickers" or symbols that represent individual companies. Now we can run through our rpevious list and call the API.

We want to see if there is a relationship between the gross profit (how much the company is earning total) and how much they are investing in their research.

To do this, we need to append to our previous list and select the information we want from the API call since there is much more data on the company's income statement than we care about at this moment.

In [4]:
for index, row in constituents.iterrows():
    # Try statement due to fields missing, etc.
    try:
        # Retrieving income statement from API for the ticker
        row_income_statement = si.get_income_statement(row.Symbol)
        if(row_income_statement.shape[1]<2):
            constituents.drop(index)
        else:
            # Saving the desired data for gross profit and r&d
            research_prev = row_income_statement.iloc[:, 1]['researchDevelopment']
            grossProfit_prev = row_income_statement.iloc[:, 1]['grossProfit']
            grossProfit_rec = row_income_statement.iloc[:, 0]['grossProfit']
        
            if(research_prev == None or grossProfit_prev == None or grossProfit_rec == None):
                constituents.drop(index)
            else:
                # Appending to our constituents dataframe
                row["grossProfit_prev"] = grossProfit_prev
                row["grossProfit_rec"] = grossProfit_rec
                row["reasearchDevelopment_prev"] = research_prev
    except:
        constituents.drop(index)

DONE

DATA MANAGEMENT

Now that we have the raw data, we need to do some cleaning because some companies do not release how much they spend on R&D. That means removing rows from our dataframe from where there is no R&D available in the most recent and second most recent yearly earnings.

Additionally, everything needs to be relative. A large company that spends more on R&D than a smaller company does not tell us anything. That is where gross profit comes in. Gross profit is what a company makes before all expenses are made. Now we can find how large of a percentage the company spends their revenue on for improving their product.

For now, we only care about the increase in one year intervals as we want some quick returns and need to find companies that will carry the index's performance. Additionally, much of the API returns missing years so we will for now ignore the fact that we are grabbing company reports from varying years. In the future, it will be best to try and get ones from the same year. The reason for this is national and international news can affect the market as a whole. For instance, this year's correction has caused the market to go down due to increase in money printed which leads to inflation.

Research and development % = research and development (year X) / gross profit (year X)

Furthermore, we need a metric for performance of a company. That is where we compare across more than on year. We will again use gross profit here:

company performance = gross profit (year X) / gross profit (year Y)

This will give us a percentage increase in gross profit between two years.

More information on what the income statement is: https://www.investopedia.com/articles/04/022504.asp

What a market correction is: https://www.schwab.com/learn/story/market-correction-what-does-it-mean

import numpy

#Creating new columns
constituents["researchDevelopmentP"] = None
constituents["increase"] = None
for index, row in constituents.iterrows():
    if(row["grossProfit_rec"] == None or row["grossProfit_prev"] == None or row["reasearchDevelopment_prev"] == None):
        # Removing rows with missing data
        constituents.drop(index, inplace=True)
    else:        
        # Calculating and setting to new column
        row["increase"] = row["grossProfit_rec"]/row["grossProfit_prev"]
        row["researchDevelopmentP"] = float(row["reasearchDevelopment_prev"]/row["grossProfit_prev"])

EXPLORATORY DATA ANALYSIS

Now that we have the curated information, we can then create vizualizations to find some immediate and clear meaning behind the data.

We will first be using regular Pandas to plot as it is quick and dirty since we can directly call it's function without need to import.

We will set the x value to the percent spent on R&D and the y value to the % gross income increase, because we want to see if there's any correlation between the two.

Pandas graph resource: https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.plot.html

A simple scatterplot is good, but much more information can be conveyed. For this, seaborn will be used as it allows for easy color categorization for the sectors of the companies. Additionally, we will fit a line of regression to draw the general trend. This will also be used via seaborn since it allows for more complex and specific usage compared to Pandas. Scatterplots also hold some other key features such as showing outliers (which we crop), as well as if there is no correlation between two variables.

The type of visualization is crucial as there are multiple ways to show the relationships given different contexts. A few other examples are boxplots and violinplots when comparing between categories. Here, I chose scatterplot because I would like to draw line of regression to quickly see relationships. This can help determine whether high R&D costs hurt or help a company.

In [59]:
import random
import seaborn as sns

# Changing the datatype to prevent errors do not like strings, so we create a copy of the current dataframe
constituents_copy = constituents.copy()
constituents_copy = constituents_copy.drop(["Sector", "Name", "Symbol"], axis=1)
#Getting unique sectors for the dataframe in order to assign colors to them
sector = constituents["Sector"].unique()
fg = sns.relplot(data=constituents, x = "researchDevelopmentP", y="increase", hue="Sector", hue_order=sector)
# Changing to float64 type so we can draw line of regression onto the graph
sns.regplot(x="researchDevelopmentP", y="increase", data=constituents_copy.astype('float64'), scatter=False)
fg.set(xlim=(-0.1, 0.5), ylim=(0, 2), xlabel="Research & Development %", ylabel="Gross Income Increase", title="Increase of Gross Income Given R&D Expenses")

As we can see, there is a general positive relation between the % of capital used in research and development and the increase in gross income. We can further distinguish this data by separating them and drawing separate lines of regression for the sectors. Overgeneralizing is a major pitfall we can avoid by continuously determining whether or not data need to be further subcategorized and avoiding irrelevant information being displayed.

In [62]:
# Iterating the sectors and grouping the dataframe by them
for sec in sector:
    curr = constituents.loc[constituents["Sector"] == sec]
    # Plotting each sectors into their own subplots
    fg = sns.relplot(data=curr, x = "researchDevelopmentP", y="increase", hue="Sector", hue_order=sector)
    
    curr = curr.drop(["Sector", "Name", "Symbol"], axis=1)
    sns.regplot(x="researchDevelopmentP", y="increase", data=curr.astype('float64'), scatter=False)
    fg.set(xlabel="Research & Development %", ylabel="Gross Income Increase", title="Increase of Gross Income Given R&D Expenses in "+sec)

Though some graphs do not have enough data, companies in health care do not seem to benefit tremendously from R&D whereas IT and industrial companies do. A hypothesis as to why this might be the case is that IT and industrial products are always shown to the media and thus the public. Additionally, health care products are heavily controlled and regulated by the government.

The addition of linear regression is especially useful because it can draw out trends very quickly and is simple to understand. We can then try and understand why or how the trends have certain characteristics and further pursue applicable knowledge.

This is great proof when assuming that the information given is sufficient that although the big picture points one way, we must make sure that that is the case for certain compartments, otherwise we make wrong decisions. For instance, if we were to just make a blanket statement that R&D costs are good, we will end up losing returns on companies in the materials sector or opportunity cost in IT companies.

CONCLUSION

The process we see here can definitely be improved here, but we at least have a working proof of concept. What we can take away from this is that the sectors in which the companies are in play a large role in how much expenses affect their performance. To be more precise, IT and Industrial companies with high R&D are promising candidates for growth within the year. This does not mean, however, they will not underperform so be very careful with the information given. Furthermore, this shows that given so many options to make (or lose) money, safe investing is always an option and using data to create educated and responsible investing decisions is still possible.

In hindsight, it might've been better to make the tradeoff to larger array of companies rather than conforming ourselves to the S&P500. That way, we can have more accurate line of regression given there are more data points. Additionally, we can draw insight for sectors that were lacking such as Energy and Utilities. We can also look for other data such as revenue, operational exepenses, the list goes on.

Another approach other than linear regression that can be used is machine learning models to train and test against. This can be done by having separated the data between training and testing, training the model using one, and then seeing how accurate it is by having the test data used for your model and comparing it with the real values. Some machine models that can be used in this instance are linear SVM, non-linear-SVM, and k-NN classification.
